The order of precedence between `:hover` and `:active` pseudo-classes in CSS is determined by the order in which they are declared in your stylesheet. This is due to the fact that both pseudo-classes have the same specificity.

If `:hover` is declared after `:active`, it will take precedence over `:active`. This means that if a user clicks on an element (activating the `:active` state) and continues to hover over it, the `:hover` styles will be applied instead of the `:active` styles.

Here's an example:

```css
button:active {
    background-color: red;
}

button:hover {
    background-color: blue;
}
```

In this case, even if the button is clicked (which would normally trigger the `:active` state), the button will appear blue (the `:hover` state) as long as the user's cursor remains over the button.

However, if you reverse the order of the pseudo-classes in your CSS:

```css
button:hover {
    background-color: blue;
}

button:active {
    background-color: red;
}
```

In this case, when the button is clicked, it will turn red (the `:active` state), even if the user's cursor is still hovering over the button.

So, the order of `:hover` and `:active` in your CSS can impact the visual feedback your user receives when interacting with clickable elements on your page. To ensure the `:active` state is visible when a user clicks an element, it's generally recommended to declare `:active` after `:hover` in your CSS.

