Here's a detailed implementation of the `isValidEmail` and `isStrongPassword` functions required by the server code:

```javascript
function isValidEmail(email) {
  const emailRegex = /^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/;
  return emailRegex.test(email);
}

function isStrongPassword(password) {
  const passwordRegex = new RegExp("^(?=.*[a-z])(?=.*[A-Z])(?=.*[0-9])(?=.*[!@#$%^&*])(?=.{8,})");
  return passwordRegex.test(password);
}
```

These functions can be used as follows:

1. `isValidEmail(email)`: This function checks if the given email is in the correct format. In this case, the function uses a regular expression to determine if the email is valid.

2. `isStrongPassword(password)`: This function checks the strength of the password based on certain criteria. The function uses a regular expression to ensure that the password is at least 8 characters long and contains at least one lowercase letter, one uppercase letter, one digit, and one special character ([!@#$%^&*)]. These criteria are considered strong password requirements.

Here's a detailed explanation of the regular expression in `isStrongPassword(password)`:

- `(?=.*[a-z])`: This is a positive lookahead that ensures there is at least one lowercase letter in the password.
- `(?=.*[A-Z])`: This is a positive lookahead that ensures there is at least one uppercase letter in the password.
- `(?=.*[0-9])`: This is a positive lookahead that ensures there is at least one digit in the password.
- `(?=.*[!@#$%^&*])`: This is a positive lookahead that ensures there is at least one special character from the set [!@#$%^&*] in the password.
- `(?=.{8,})`: This ensures the password is at least 8 characters long.

Using these functions in the server code will ensure that registration requests have valid email addresses and strong passwords.

Three.ArcballControls is not a native control in Three.js; instead, you need to use an external library called `ArcballControls`. However, you can achieve a 360-degree camera rotation with the native `OrbitControls` in Three.js.

In the following example, I'll show you how to set up a simple scene with a cube and `OrbitControls` for rotating the camera around the cube:

1. First, load required scripts:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
</head>
<body>
  <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/three.js/r128/three.min.js"></script>
  <script src="https://threejs.org/examples/jsm/controls/OrbitControls.js"></script>
  <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

2. Create a new `script.js` file and implement the following code:

```javascript
// Set up the scene, camera, and renderer
let scene = new THREE.Scene();
let camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera(75, window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight, 0.1, 1000);
let renderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer({antialias: true});
renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
document.body.appendChild(renderer.domElement);

// Set up OrbitControls
const controls = new THREE.OrbitControls(camera, renderer.domElement);

// Create a cube
let geometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry();
let material = new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial({color: 0x00ff00});
let cube = new THREE.Mesh(geometry, material);
scene.add(cube);

// Set camera position
camera.position.z = 5;
camera.position.y = 1;
controls.update();

function animate() {
  requestAnimationFrame(animate);

  // Render the scene
  controls.update();
  renderer.render(scene, camera);
}

animate();
```

Now you can use your mouse or touchpad to rotate the camera 360 degrees around the cube. The `OrbitControls` allow you to orbit the camera around the target (which is the center by default) by dragging the mouse/touchpad.

By adjusting the `camera.position` and the `controls.target` properties, you can change the initial position of the camera and the object it orbits.
